\b\fs34 \cf0 Why RepQuarks?
\fs28 \

\b0 \
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\fs24 \cf0 To add or modify Classes in SuperCollider one places the files that contain Class definition code inside the folder "Extensions" under 
\f1 Platform.userAppSupportDir
\f0  (for more info see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "file:///Applications/SuperCollider/Help/Extending%20and%20Customizing%20SC/Using-Extensions.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \ul \ulc2 Using-Extensions}}). The\cf3  {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "file:///Applications/SuperCollider/Help/Extending%20and%20Customizing%20SC/Quarks/Quarks.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 Quarks}}\cf0  mechanism allows one package a group of classes in a folder and to add or remove it via GUI.  This makes it possible to organize code in packages, which makes code management easier. A Quark is installed by placing an alias of its folder in the Extensions directory. Normal Quarks are downloaded by SuperCollider with the statement 
\f1 \cf5 Quarks.gui
\f0 \cf0  and are all placed in the folder  
\f1 Platform.userAppSupportDir ++ Quarks
\f0 . RepQuarks makes it possible to combine different quark projects which exist independently in different folders, without having to copy these in the global Quarks directory. This gives additional freedom in working with multiple projects while keeping their files separate, and is especially valuable for sharing code with other people independently from the global Quarks. 
\f1\fs18 \
\

\f0\b\fs36 What RepQuarks are and how they work
\f1\b0\fs18 \

\fs24 \

\f0 RepQuarks are Quarks whose code resides locally, that is, on the computer where the SuperCollider client ("lang")  is running. There can be any number of local folders anywhere in the system that contain RepQuarks. To add the quarks of a local folder to SuperCollider, follow these 3 steps:\
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}Define an empty subclass of RepQuarks and puts its definition file at the top level of the folder containing the RepQuarks. The name of the subclass may be anything any valid unique class name. \
{\listtext	2.	}Place an alias of the definition file \cb6 in a subfolder\cb1  in the Extensions folder of your 
\f1 Platform.userAppSupportDir. 
\f0 \cb7 The name of the alias should end in .sc. \cb8  Why ???\cb1 \
{\listtext	3.	}Recompile SuperCollider. A new menu entry for the new RepQuarks group is created in the Quarks menu. \
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural
\cf0 \
The structure of a RepQuarks folder is the same as that of a normal Quarks folder. It is also possible to group several Quarks folders inside a RepQuarks folder, or to put these inside a subfolder named Quarks. All 4 different folder configuration types are described below. \
\

